I actually think we can, and I think we've accidentally found something that could become Ledger's signature mechanic.

I wouldn't merge all of Option 4 into Option 1. I'd borrow one idea from it.

The Market Has Two Stages

Instead of thinking about "the game running out of assets," think of the game as having two economic eras.

Stage 1 — Growth Economy

At the start:

Players buy assets from the Bank.
Everyone is building their portfolio.
Loans are common.
Investments happen.
People are racing to establish themselves.

This is the "startup" phase.

Stage 2 — Mature Economy

Eventually...

The bank has sold every Ace, King, Queen, Jack, etc.

At that moment, something interesting happens naturally.

The bank says:

"We're sold out."

Now the economy belongs to the players.

From this point forward:

Auctions become common.
Private sales become valuable.
Hostile Takeovers become frequent.
Alliances matter more.
Investments become more strategic.

The game naturally shifts from building wealth to fighting over wealth.

I absolutely love that.

It feels like real economies.

So where does Option 4 fit?

Not as unlimited assets.

Instead...

The Bank Can Issue New Assets

But only under extraordinary circumstances.

Think of it like a company issuing new shares.

Example:

All four Aces have been sold.

Normally...

That's it.

But...

The Bank has one emergency action:

Corporate Expansion

The Bank may issue one additional Ace into the economy.

BUT...

Instead of costing 40 LC...

It now costs something like:

120 LC.

Why?

Because it's creating a brand-new premium corporation.

This does a few beautiful things:

The bank never completely breaks.
New players still have a comeback option if they're extremely rich.
It doesn't undermine scarcity because it's intentionally expensive.
It's so expensive that players will usually prefer buying from another player first.

So 95% of the time, the secondary market is still the best option.

Even Better...

We don't let the bank do this automatically.

Instead, make it a player decision.

Example:

A player clicks:

Request Corporate Expansion

The bank responds:

"Issue a new Ace-class corporation for 120 LC?"

Now the player chooses.

Most of the time they'll think:

"Forget it. I'll just negotiate with another player."

Exactly what we want.

This creates an invisible price ceiling.

Suppose I own an Ace.

If I try to sell it for 180 LC...

Everyone knows:

"Why would I pay 180? I can just issue a new one for 120."

Suddenly I have to lower my asking price.

That's a beautiful economic balancing mechanism.

What this means for Ledger

The economy has a clear progression:

Early Game

Build.
Borrow.
Invest.
Buy from the bank.

↓

Mid Game

Bank inventory dries up.
Scarcity appears.
Negotiation begins.

