Era Four

Corporate War

Hostile takeovers.

Emergency investments.

Legal pressure.

Bankruptcies.

Massive negotiations.

Everything becomes tense.

Era Five

Endgame

Only strongest businesses remain.

Every decision matters.

Every takeover matters.

Every negotiation matters.

One mistake ends your company.

PLAYER ELIMINATION

Ledger intentionally allows elimination.

Why?

Because elimination creates pressure.

Pressure creates excitement.

Excitement creates memorable stories.

Nobody wants to become the next company to collapse.

PLAYER PSYCHOLOGY

Ledger constantly creates emotional highs.

Buying first Ace.

Getting first investment.

Paying off first loan.

Winning first auction.

Surviving first takeover.

Launching successful takeover.

Building biggest company.

Winning match.

Each moment feels meaningful.

WHY LEDGER FEELS DIFFERENT

Unlike Monopoly...

Money doesn't appear randomly.

Unlike Poker...

Luck isn't the deciding factor.

Unlike Chess...

Negotiation exists.

Unlike Catan...

Players create the economy.

Ledger combines:

Economics

Strategy

Negotiation

Politics

Risk Management

Business

Psychology

into one competitive multiplayer experience.

CORE DESIGN PHILOSOPHY

Every mechanic in Ledger must satisfy four principles:

Simple to understand. A new player should learn the basics within a few minutes.
Deep to master. Experienced players should continuously discover better strategies through negotiation, timing, investment decisions, and market control.
Meaningful choices. Every decision—borrowing, investing, buying, launching a takeover, or helping another player—should involve a real trade-off.
Player-driven stories. The most memorable moments should come from player interactions, not scripted events: desperate alliances, dramatic takeover defenses, risky investments, and unexpected betrayals.

